article.description:
The Sparks played without leading scorer Lisa Leslie, but
Seattle's Lauren Jackson scored in the wrong basket after
rebounding a missed free throw and that helped the Sparks pull away for an 80-68 victory over the Storm on Tuesday.
article.headline: Sparks win with a little help from Storm center
article.linkText: Leslie out sick but Sparks still get past Storm
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- The Los Angeles Sparks got some help from the other team's 6-foot-5 center on a night theirs was out sick. The Sparks played without leading scorer Lisa Leslie, but Seattle's Lauren Jackson scored in the wrong basket after rebounding a missed free throw and that helped the Sparks pull away for an 80-68 victory over the Storm on Tuesday night. "We thank her for that,'' Los Angeles coach Michael Cooper said. "It was nice to have two points. But the way we were playing in the second half, that wasn't going to be the difference in the game.'' Mwadi Mabika scored 16 of her 23 points in the second half and DeLisha Milton added 20 points as Leslie's fill-in as Los Angeles (8-1) won its fifth straight. They each had nine rebounds. Tamecka Dixon had 16 points and Latasha Byears added 10 and the Sparks were able to establish their transition game right away. Jackson scored 23 points for her own team to go with 10 rebounds and three assists. Sue Bird added 12 points and five assists for the Storm (4-5). Mabika made two free throws with 11:34 left to give the Sparks a 53-52 lead, then she scored the next time down the floor and was fouled. When she missed the ensuing free throw, Jackson rebounded it and scored an uncontested layup into the Sparks' basket with 11:11 to go for a five-point Los Angeles lead. Jackson, who had just re-entered the game, wore an embarrassed look as she hustled down the court to get back on offense. "I just wasn't thinking,'' she said. "I was focused so much on scoring that I did it in the wrong basket. I've done it before -- when I was 10 years old. I talked to my friend Sonja (ex-teammate Sonja Henning) and she said I looked really good when I did it because I had a big smile on my face.'' Milton followed Jackson's play with a 3-pointer on the Sparks' next possession and the Storm never got close again. It was another big game for Mabika, who scored 19 points, including two 3-pointers in overtime, to lead the Sparks over Sacramento on Saturday. "I'm not doing nothing really,'' she said. "I'm healthy. My knees are feeling great, my body's feeling great. I've been very offensive minded and I'm just penetrating more. Last year I was just shooting from the perimeter so I decided to add this into my game.'' Leslie was scratched from the lineup because of flulike symptoms. She is questionable for Friday's game against Minnesota in Los Angeles. Seattle took advantage of six quick turnovers by Los Angeles in the first half and led by as many as seven points before the Sparks came back to tie the game at 22 on Nicky McCrimmon's steal and basket with 7:52 left. The Sparks led 38-37 at halftime. "We played a tough game tonight,'' Storm coach Lin Dunn said. "But we did not play a complete game. We went away from some of the basics and they cost us. It was the little things that beat us tonight.'' And the big things -- like scoring for the wrong team. "It was funny,'' Mabika said. "I don't know what she was thinking, but it worked for us.''

Game notes
Forward Amanda Lassiter made her Storm debut, finishing with seven points and six rebounds. She was acquired in a trade with Houston on Monday that sent veteran guard Sonja Henning to the Comets. ... Cooper said before the game that his team's level of play has been "disappointing'' because the Sparks have been "playing to our opponents' level.''
